==English==
===Etymology===
From Old French [[fomenter]], from late Latin [[fomentare]], from Latin [[fomentum]] ‘lotion’, from [[fovere]] ‘heat, cherish’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/fə'mɛnt/}}

====Homophones====
*[[ferment]]

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-consonant|foment||}}
# To apply a [[poultice]] to; to [[bathe]] with a cloth or sponge
#:*'''1904''': The maid had entered with us, and began once more to '''foment''' the bruise upon her mistress's brow. — Arthur Conan Doyle, ‘The Adventure of the Abbey Grange’ (Norton 2005, p.1178)
# To cherish and [[promote]], to [[encourage]]; to [[instigate]]

See also: [[fomentation]]

